external.description: Coastal sea level around Greenland has now been projected to fall by as much as 13 feet (4 meters) by 2100, overturning expectations for a world defined by rising oceans. As the island sheds ice at extraordinary speed, its own shoreline may pull away from the sea even as meltwater drives global waters higher. Greenland rises as ice sheets melt Along Greenland’s coastline, long-running measurements show the ground lifting steadily as the ice sheet thins. Analyzing those records, Lauren Lewright of Columbia University demonstrated that this uplift is strong enough to outpace ocean rise and force local sea levels downward. The projected retreat is greatest along western and southern Greenland, where ice loss is expected to accelerate throughout the century. That uneven pattern means the scale and timing of the drop cannot be understood without examining the physical forces that are reshaping the island from below. Two forces lower sea levels Year by year, Greenland loses around 200 billion tons of ice, and that loss pushes local sea level down.
